    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-24T03:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-24T03:35:00-05:00" n="475"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d475">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">391.1163 Lutheran Orient Mission/95:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merriam</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Teheran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-24T12:00:00+03:25"
                            >March 24, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 3 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>24. Lutheran missionaries at Saujbulak in Azerbaijan have been ordered to leave
                    by the local governor. This morning I asked the acting Foreign Minister to delay
                    action pending full investigation and drew his attention to the exchange of
                    notes dated May 14, 1928,<note n="22" xml:id="d475fn22">For text of notes, see
                            <ref target="frus1928v03#pg_724">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1928, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 724</ref>.</note> relating to
                    missionary activities.</p>
                <p>He did not mention <hi rend="italic">Mirror</hi> article<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d475fn23">The article in the New York <hi rend="italic">Daily
                            Mirror</hi> which led to the withdrawal of the Iranian representatives
                        in the United States. See memorandum by the Under Secretary of State, March
                        14, and following correspondence, <ref target="#pg_350">pp. 350</ref>
                        ff.</note> during our friendly interview and of course I refrained from
                    doing so.</p>
                <p>He said that Anayat Ollah Sami’i heretofore Iranian Minister at Baghdad has been
                    appointed Minister of Foreign Affairs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merriam</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
